WEBVTT

00:01.442 --> 00:02.003
Good morning.

00:02.464 --> 00:05.752
My name is Holly and I am the Bowmanville site pastor.

00:05.832 --> 00:11.204
Good morning to you watching in Port Perry, in Pickering, in Ajax, watching online.

00:11.605 --> 00:14.511
Maybe you were away for the long weekend and you're catching up with us.

00:14.712 --> 00:17.618
I'm really excited to spend this time together with you.

00:18.370 --> 00:22.538
If you know me, you probably know that I grew up as a competitive swimmer.

00:22.898 --> 00:35.001
I started from a really early age, I started in elementary school, and I swam for the Pickering Swim Club, all throughout elementary school, through high school, and then in college, I swam for the University of Illinois.

00:35.602 --> 00:36.704
And swimming was my thing.

00:36.864 --> 00:40.050
I spent every spare moment in the pool.

00:40.130 --> 00:47.002
But before I found my thing, my parents really wanted me to try new things and to try to find hobbies and interests.

00:47.022 --> 00:50.709
So as a little kid, they signed me up for a lot of different activities.

00:51.510 --> 00:56.720
I tried soccer and I cared a lot more about picking flowers than I did about scoring goals.

00:57.401 --> 01:04.754
I tried skating and I got to put stickers on my helmet and that was about the best part for me and just like fell a lot on the ice.

01:05.154 --> 01:10.462
I tried singing camp one summer and there's a reason I am not on the worship team.

01:11.143 --> 01:17.813
I tried piano lessons and for an eight year old, like I hated it with like a deep fiery passion.

01:17.833 --> 01:25.023
I would try to get Miss Joanne to talk as much as I could for the half hour that I had the lesson for because it just literally meant less playing time.

01:26.105 --> 01:32.274
And so the doozy of all doozies, when I think about all the activities and sports that I tried,

01:32.834 --> 01:34.858
It had to be dance.

01:34.878 --> 01:39.007
I started out in like a combo class, so it was ballet, jazz, and tap.

01:39.027 --> 01:39.989
And it was fine.

01:40.049 --> 01:45.160
Like, we're all young and can follow basic instructions, so it wasn't a total disaster.

01:45.220 --> 01:49.810
But I definitely didn't have rhythm, and I definitely didn't have flexibility.

01:49.890 --> 01:53.795
And so as that year came to a close, my mom asked me if I wanted to sign up again.

01:53.815 --> 01:58.741
And I was like, yeah, all of my friends, all of the cool girls are doing this new thing called Acro.

01:59.141 --> 02:02.826
And it's this combination of gymnastics and dance together.

02:02.866 --> 02:06.370
And so I begged my mom to sign me up for it.

02:06.751 --> 02:08.853
And she was like fine, okay, we can do it.

02:09.694 --> 02:14.460
So don't I show up to the first day of Acro without the skills to touch my toes.

02:14.900 --> 02:19.506
Let alone do a bridge or a back walkover or even a proper cartwheel.

02:20.162 --> 02:21.343
And that's the thing about dance.

02:21.564 --> 02:26.790
You have to have the same skills as the other dancers in order to perform a number.

02:27.190 --> 02:34.639
You have to follow the steps aligned and in tandem with the other dancers for the performance to look complete, for it to look like it makes sense.

02:35.159 --> 02:47.794
And so when one kid, me, had to crab walk in the final recital while all the other girls were doing perfectly beautiful bridge walks, it really did affect the entire group's ability to perform it.

02:48.450 --> 02:53.456
And I want to draw a parallel from this embarrassing story of my childhood to what I'm talking about today.

02:53.737 --> 02:56.000
And it's this idea of Shalom.

02:56.560 --> 03:00.586
And as we unpack this name of God together, Yahweh Shalom.

03:01.266 --> 03:05.692
Now, Shalom might be the only Hebrew word that you kind of know off the top of your head.

03:06.253 --> 03:09.797
And we know it to have this loose translation of peace.

03:10.398 --> 03:16.626
But actually, it's quite difficult to translate this word because of the depth and the vastness of this word.

03:17.378 --> 03:23.927
But the truest maybe best definition that we can come up with in the English is this idea of completeness or of wholeness.

03:24.568 --> 03:27.832
It's derived from the word shalem, which means whole or complete.

03:28.373 --> 03:38.466
And though we know shalom as peace, it's not only the absence of conflict or of strife or discord, but it's actually something better in its place.

03:39.447 --> 03:41.470
It extends beyond peace.

03:41.490 --> 03:47.378
It refers to something with a lot of different pieces and a lot of moving parts that make a whole together.

03:47.586 --> 03:58.762
And when one of those parts is missing or is fractured or is doing the crab walk, it disrupts the state of Shalom and therefore has a need to be restored or to be fixed.

03:58.782 --> 04:06.954
Shalom is harmony in which all of the pieces are fitting together and that peace is coming from that interconnectedness.

04:07.455 --> 04:15.026
It's the state in which all things are aligned with God's perfect plan and humanity lives in a flourishing unity

04:15.426 --> 04:17.769
with one another, with nature, and with God.

04:18.390 --> 04:20.874
In the beginning, God created the world in Shalom.

04:21.134 --> 04:28.846
We walked in the garden with God in Shalom, but sin fractured that peace, and it led to this brokenness, division, and suffering.

04:30.388 --> 04:42.546
Shalom was a vision that God had for the nation of Israel, and bringing Shalom or restoring Shalom was the responsibility we see God give many of the leaders in scripture that we know so well.

04:42.850 --> 04:48.977
He uses them to guide his people back into Shalom, into a state of wholeness.

04:49.698 --> 04:52.842
And today we read this story out of the book of Judges.

04:52.922 --> 05:01.292
And we see this like really interesting human interaction between God and one of the leaders that he is giving this task to.

05:01.352 --> 05:06.418
He's entrusting this task of leading his people back into Shalom.

05:07.266 --> 05:15.362
And God has revealed as not only having a dream of Shalom for his people, but actually it's like the very nature of who he is.

05:15.482 --> 05:17.145
It's the fabric of his being.

05:17.546 --> 05:19.550
It's one of his very own names.

05:20.372 --> 05:27.826
But to understand this particular story where God gets this name, we need to know exactly where we are in the story of the Israelites.

05:27.970 --> 05:33.035
And so the book of Judges starts out where the Israelites are new homeowners in the promised land.

05:33.055 --> 05:34.256
They have just moved there.

05:34.356 --> 05:36.638
Joshua has just taken them into the promised land.

05:37.059 --> 05:44.106
And the people in the surrounding area who would have been their neighbors are not super pleased about that development to say the least.

05:44.786 --> 05:46.828
And all the Israelites are in this wrestle, right?

05:46.848 --> 05:49.171
They're trying to drive out these other people groups.

05:49.511 --> 05:56.658
They're trying to stay faithful to the covenant that they had made with Yahweh all the while, trying not to worship other gods.

05:57.346 --> 06:02.212
and therefore be led astray by these morally corrupt neighboring people groups.

06:02.933 --> 06:05.937
Now, right before chapter 6 was Deborah's story of leadership.

06:05.997 --> 06:08.860
Deborah was a judge and maybe you know that story really well.

06:08.941 --> 06:12.745
And so that leads the Israelites into Shalom for 40 years.

06:13.306 --> 06:14.668
But what happens in year 41?

06:14.768 --> 06:15.849
Exactly.

06:15.889 --> 06:19.634
What you think happens, the Israelites do evil in the eyes of the Lord.

06:20.546 --> 06:26.672
Judges 6 1 says that the Israelites did evil in the eyes of the Lord.

06:27.113 --> 06:30.296
And for seven years he gave them into the hands of the Midianites.

06:30.777 --> 06:39.326
Because the power of Midian was so oppressive, the Israelites prepared shelters for themselves in the mountain class, the caves and strongholds.

06:39.926 --> 06:47.314
Whenever the Israelites planted their crops, the Midianites, the Amalekites and the other Eastern peoples invaded the country.

06:48.162 --> 06:55.617
They camped on the land and they ruined all of the crops all the way to Gaza and did not spare a living thing for Israel.

06:56.138 --> 06:57.961
Neither sheep nor cattle nor donkeys.

06:58.442 --> 07:07.680
They came up to their livestock with their tents and to their tents and they swarmed like locusts and it was impossible to count them on their camels.

07:08.121 --> 07:10.706
They invaded the land to ravage it.

07:11.266 --> 07:15.012
So here's this picture of Israel in complete and utter despair.

07:15.413 --> 07:18.077
They are living in dens and caves like animals.

07:18.438 --> 07:21.843
Their crop and their livestock has been completely destroyed.

07:21.863 --> 07:28.695
So not only are their food sources depleted, but they're also in economic ruin as a people group.

07:29.236 --> 07:30.738
They are not thriving.

07:31.426 --> 07:39.957
And that kind of weird fact about the Midianites on their camels, well, it actually gave them like a tactical advantage on oppressing the Israelites.

07:39.977 --> 07:47.987
Everyone with the spiritual gift of mercy, I'm sure right now, has to be reminded that the suppression wasn't just random.

07:48.848 --> 07:52.914
It was the impact of Israel doing evil in the eyes of the Lord.

07:53.294 --> 07:56.338
They were worshiping other gods besides Yahweh.

07:57.314 --> 08:00.098
And these nations were doing things like sacrificing their children.

08:00.158 --> 08:13.619
This wasn't just the Israelites trying to be friendly to their neighbors, but it was their complete abandonment of Yahweh, moving away from worshipping Him and moving towards worshipping other gods who had not saved them and not come through for them.

08:14.480 --> 08:19.468
Verse 6, Midian so impoverished the Israelites that they cried out to the Lord for help.

08:20.149 --> 08:26.258
And God, because He is God of mercy and of second chances, answers them.

08:26.498 --> 08:28.102
but not without a discussion about it first.

08:28.824 --> 08:37.266
When the Israelites cried out to the Lord because of Midian, verse 8, he sent them a prophet who said, this is what the Lord, the God of Israel, says.

08:37.538 --> 08:41.103
I brought you out out of Egypt, out of the land of slavery.

08:41.343 --> 08:47.993
I have rescued you from the hand of the Egyptians, and I delivered you from the hand of all your oppressors.

08:48.533 --> 08:51.778
I drove them out before you, and I gave you their land.

08:52.218 --> 08:54.842
And I said to you, I am the Lord your God.

08:55.183 --> 09:01.271
Do not worship the gods of the Amorites in whose land you live, but you have not listened to me."

09:02.333 --> 09:06.258
God references his prior savings of the Israelite people.

09:06.498 --> 09:07.820
He comes with receipts.

09:08.221 --> 09:14.931
He reminds them all about the other times that he has swooped in to save them, the covenant that he established with them.

09:14.971 --> 09:17.535
And they have been blatantly ignoring it.

09:18.396 --> 09:28.491
He recalls their Yahweh given victories, not victory, but victories, all of the times that he has come through for his people.

09:28.571 --> 09:35.602
He reminds them that they are stuck in this cycle of saying they will follow and trust him, but never actually follow through.

09:35.842 --> 09:38.486
which is the cause of their current oppression.

09:39.227 --> 09:42.011
But their own choices have put them there.

09:42.833 --> 09:45.897
But God is mercy and he has compassion for his people.

09:46.338 --> 09:51.366
His desire to see his people in Shalom is too strong to leave them in despair.

09:52.387 --> 10:04.466
Verse 11, the angel of the Lord came and sat down under the oak in Oprah, not Oprah, which I probably will end up saying at some point today, because it's spelled very similar, that belonged to Jewish, the Bezerite.

10:04.898 --> 10:09.646
where his son Gideon was threshing wheat in a wine press to keep it from the Midianites.

10:10.407 --> 10:18.842
For those of us who are not wheat-threshing experts, the wine press was a weird place to thresh wheat, but it was a great place to hide.

10:19.904 --> 10:29.179
God finds a man in literal hiding to be the leader of his people and to start this process of deliverance for the nation of Israel.

10:30.221 --> 10:30.802
Verse 12,

10:31.202 --> 10:33.125
Then the angel of the Lord appeared to Gideon.

10:33.165 --> 10:36.150
He said, the Lord is with you, mighty warrior.

10:36.190 --> 10:42.620
The Lord is with you, mighty warrior, who is maybe not feeling so mighty as he is hiding in the wine press.

10:43.141 --> 10:46.006
Gideon speaking to God's messenger replies.

10:46.066 --> 10:48.850
He says, pardon me, my Lord.

10:49.698 --> 10:52.803
But if the Lord is with us, why has all this happened to us?

10:53.203 --> 10:59.753
Where are all the wonders that our ancestors told us about when they said, did not the Lord bring you up out of Egypt?

11:00.013 --> 11:03.238
But now the Lord has abandoned us and given us into the hand of Midian.

11:04.079 --> 11:14.194
I get to read it like that because the commentary literally said, Gideon rather cheekily picks up the words that Yahweh had previously spoken and challenges him with them.

11:14.786 --> 11:34.557
And while Gideon is wrong in complaining that God has not come through for them, what he absolutely has, I honestly just appreciate a good wrestle in Scripture because doesn't it just remind you that these people are broken and sinful and struggle with the exact same things that we do right now in our relationship with God?

11:35.880 --> 11:39.986
But God indulges him even as he's in his weakness.

11:40.642 --> 11:46.713
not because he owes us, but because he loves us, not because he owes Gideon because he loves him.

11:47.113 --> 11:51.281
God is not put off by this gesture from Gideon and God is not put off by yours either.

11:51.321 --> 11:56.209
Instead, he turns his face towards Gideon and he commissions him.

11:57.211 --> 12:03.022
Verse 14, the Lord turned to him and said, go in the strength that you have and save Israel out of Midian's ham.

12:03.823 --> 12:05.586
Am I not sending you?

12:06.370 --> 12:11.899
And don't we just totally get it when Gideon replies, part of me, my Lord, but how can I save Israel?

12:12.380 --> 12:16.386
My clan is the weakest in Manasseh and I am the least in my family.

12:16.927 --> 12:24.639
The Lord answered, I will be with you and you will strike down all of the Midianites, leaving none alive.

12:25.380 --> 12:28.946
God graciously accommodates room

12:29.058 --> 12:43.640
for Gideon to share his doubt, but he does make sure to make reality really clear that it's not by Gideon's own strength that he is going to save his people, but it's through the Lord's, that he will lead the Israelites out of peril and back into Shalom.

12:45.342 --> 12:53.394
And then this is where he starts to clue in that perhaps maybe this might not be a messenger from the Lord, but he might actually be speaking with the Lord himself.

12:53.730 --> 12:55.112
And this is a pretty big deal.

12:55.152 --> 13:04.083
We only see this eight other times in the Old Testament where we see God takes upon himself this physical form for a really short duration.

13:04.123 --> 13:11.652
And we might be used to that idea because we now are on this side of the timeline and we understand Jesus as God in human form.

13:11.972 --> 13:14.515
But this would have been so crazy for Gideon.

13:14.896 --> 13:17.339
And I'm sure he is internally just freaking out.

13:17.959 --> 13:19.501
But we see what he does next.

13:19.922 --> 13:20.963
He double checks.

13:21.944 --> 13:23.506
Verse 17.

13:23.650 --> 13:29.919
Gideon replied, If now I have found favor in your eyes, give me a sign that this is really you talking to me.

13:30.339 --> 13:34.645
Please do not go away until I come back and bring my offering and set it before you.

13:35.186 --> 13:37.109
And the Lord said, I will wait until you return.

13:37.149 --> 13:43.738
Verse 19, Gideon went inside prepared a young goat and from an ephah of flower he made bread without yeast.

13:44.138 --> 13:49.746
Putting the meat in a basket and the broth in a pot, he brought them out and offered them to him under the oak.

13:50.562 --> 13:57.732
This wouldn't have been like a swift 20 minutes loaf of bread kind of ordeal, but this was 36 pounds of flour.

13:57.992 --> 14:02.218
So this would have taken a really long time, but God indulges Gideon.

14:02.418 --> 14:02.859
He waits.

14:03.881 --> 14:10.450
The angel of God said to him, take the meat and the unleavened bread, place them on this rock and pour out the broth and Gideon did so.

14:11.171 --> 14:16.498
And then the angel of the Lord touched the meat and the unleavened bread with the tip of the staff that was in his hand.

14:17.314 --> 14:22.060
fire flared from the rock, consuming the meat and the bread, and the angel of the Lord disappeared.

14:22.661 --> 14:30.351
When Gideon realized that it was the angel of the Lord, he exclaimed, a last sovereign Lord, I have seen the angel of the Lord face to face.

14:31.412 --> 14:39.222
And now that realization, that hunch that he had, that this might be the Lord that he's speaking to is unraveling in his mind.

14:39.542 --> 14:45.490
And the realization that no one who sees the Lord in the Old Testament lives afterwards

14:45.634 --> 14:51.039
is also playing out in his mind, and he is utterly terrified that he is gonna die.

14:51.900 --> 14:59.627
But God's character, full of patience and grace and peace throughout this whole entire encounter, continues.

15:00.588 --> 15:05.473
But the Lord said to him, peace, do not be afraid, you are not going to die.

15:06.293 --> 15:11.238
So Gideon built an altar to the Lord there and called it, the Lord is peace.

15:12.019 --> 15:13.360
Yahweh Shalom.

15:14.081 --> 15:15.442
He names this

15:15.682 --> 15:33.671
after the two things that he has experienced in his time with the Lord, Yahweh, who appeared to him and Shalom, the life-giving word that was spoken to him, the word that changes everything for him, the thing that he knows, that he knows, that he knows down in his core to be true about God.

15:33.731 --> 15:40.562
Despite what his feelings and his circumstances tell him otherwise, he knows God as peace.

15:41.474 --> 15:56.960
For Gideon, the anxiety of the call to deliver God's people is eclipsed by a greater reality of God's goodness, his completeness, his peace, the shalom that he offers Gideon in the face of fear and doubt.

15:57.882 --> 16:00.947
But God's interaction with Gideon leaves him right where he left him.

16:01.127 --> 16:02.930
I'd love to tell you that shalom just

16:03.010 --> 16:09.557
fell into place under Gideon's rule and that, you know, everything totally works out.

16:09.898 --> 16:20.830
But instead, we actually see that Gideon enters into a series of events filled with chaos and destruction and pain and fear and doubt and just war.

16:20.890 --> 16:32.082
The literal same day God commissions Gideon, God asks him to tear down his father's altar dedicated to the two gods, Ashira and Bail.

16:32.834 --> 16:35.318
the God and goddess that Israelites have been worshiping.

16:35.798 --> 16:40.005
And while that obviously ruffles some feathers because everyone wants to kill him afterwards.

16:40.325 --> 16:44.411
So he navigates that and then he has to rally an army together, which is no easy feat.

16:44.752 --> 16:46.254
And then he has some second thoughts.

16:46.775 --> 16:49.098
And he asks God for more science.

16:49.118 --> 16:53.264
This is the fleece story, if you know it, if you're familiar with it from Sunday school.

16:54.346 --> 17:02.418
And if you're not, it's essentially that God, that Gideon asks God for a very specific, and in my humble opinion, strange,

17:02.530 --> 17:06.795
sign to double check, to triple check that God is with him.

17:07.476 --> 17:08.718
We pick up in verse 36.

17:08.878 --> 17:17.409
It says, Gideon said to God, if you will save Israel by my hand, as you have promised, look, I will place a wool fleece on the threshing floor.

17:17.789 --> 17:23.897
And if there is dew on the fleece and the ground is dry, then I will know you will save Israel by my hand, as you have said.

17:23.937 --> 17:25.859
And that is what happened.

17:26.240 --> 17:28.302
Gideon rose early the next day.

17:28.342 --> 17:31.186
He squeezed the fleece and he wrung out the dew.

17:31.266 --> 17:32.668
a bowl full of water.

17:34.210 --> 17:37.674
Verse 39, then Gideon said to God, don't be angry with me.

17:37.874 --> 17:39.436
Let me just make one more request.

17:39.497 --> 17:40.958
How many of us totally do that?

17:41.739 --> 17:44.002
Allow me one more test with the fleece.

17:44.403 --> 17:48.188
But this time, make the fleece dry and let the ground be covered with dew.

17:48.688 --> 17:49.870
That night, God did so.

17:49.890 --> 17:51.592
Only the fleece was dry.

17:51.632 --> 17:53.895
All the ground was covered with dew.

17:55.137 --> 17:59.442
I'm not sure if you've ever asked God for a sign before, but I honestly love this.

17:59.746 --> 18:26.002
the God of the universe, the creator of heaven and earth made that fleece blanket or cloak or cloak or Patagonia wet and dry because he is a God who reassures he leans down to Gideon's level knowing that he is human and has worries and doubts and he shows Gideon yet again that he can trust him because he's Yahweh Shalom and that he is with him and then peace

18:26.306 --> 18:26.907
Nope, war.

18:27.267 --> 18:35.078
They head up into the fight with the Midianites, and you'd think God knowing Gideon's a little nervy and doubtful about the whole thing would give him more than he needs to win, right?

18:35.398 --> 18:35.638
Wrong.

18:35.939 --> 18:39.323
God continues to ask Gideon to get rid of men in the army.

18:39.984 --> 18:42.648
First, whoever is scared, which fair.

18:43.028 --> 18:50.578
So it starts out with about 32,000, and then, you know, a bunch of them are scared, and so we get about 10,000 men.

18:51.170 --> 18:58.962
And second, I mean, God is God, so he can enlist whoever and however he wants to be in his army, but he decides that the army will go down to the water.

18:59.362 --> 19:04.971
And whoever drinks from the water, like a dog is out and whoever drinks like the water and cups it in their hands, is in.

19:05.472 --> 19:09.958
And so that takes the army down from about 10,000 to 300 hand drinkers.

19:10.479 --> 19:20.434
And so with clay pots and torches, no weapons, God allows their army to win over the 135

19:20.674 --> 19:28.343
thousand Midianite forces with 300 men and some fire on sticks and some clay pots.

19:29.464 --> 19:30.485
And then peace in the land.

19:31.286 --> 19:34.370
But honestly, it's not really for that long.

19:34.991 --> 19:41.478
The brutal part is, is that I've just taken you on this 15-minute journey of the story of Gideon's commission and rule.

19:42.059 --> 19:44.882
But after about 40 years, Gideon dies.

19:44.994 --> 19:47.518
And the Israelites fall into the cycle again.

19:47.558 --> 19:52.346
They do evil in the sight of the Lord and they lose their shalom in their land and with God.

19:53.367 --> 20:01.420
They fall into even more destruction and even more oppression and brokenness and sin and do evil yet again in the eyes of the Lord.

20:01.480 --> 20:07.890
And when we zoom out on the Israelite story, we see the big picture of the Old Testament.

20:07.970 --> 20:19.748
We see the shattering of the shalom in the garden of Eden and that God's people are in this cyclical nature of God saving them or providing for them or coming through when they ask him to.

20:20.549 --> 20:22.111
And he captures their hearts.

20:22.171 --> 20:23.794
They worship him for a moment.

20:23.874 --> 20:33.027
And then when they're not in danger or he doesn't come through the way that they hope he will, he comes through in his own way or they get frustrated with their circumstance.

20:33.608 --> 20:35.030
They wander away.

20:35.090 --> 20:37.554
They worship other idols.

20:37.634 --> 20:39.677
other gods that did not save them.

20:40.278 --> 20:44.463
They turn their back on Yahweh and therefore fracture the shalom.

20:44.764 --> 20:48.889
He is trying so hard to create with his people again and again.

20:49.570 --> 20:52.194
And every time he tries to restore it.

20:53.135 --> 20:58.442
And this story is one trip around that cycle for us, but there are so many more.

20:59.844 --> 21:04.370
However, God in his kindness enters into chaos.

21:04.770 --> 21:11.418
He enters into brokenness, into strife, into discord, this cycle of wandering away from our Creator.

21:11.999 --> 21:15.663
And he gives us true shalom through his son, Jesus.

21:16.404 --> 21:22.972
Jesus steps into the world that he created as the ultimate fulfillment of God's dream for shalom for humanity.

21:23.373 --> 21:34.386
He lived a perfect life in harmony with the Father, exemplifying love and compassion and reconciliation with every single choice and every single action that he makes on earth.

21:34.690 --> 21:37.953
Jesus expresses the father's heart for Shalom.

21:38.154 --> 21:52.389
Every time he writes something that has been wrong, every teaching that he shares, every demon he drives out, every healing he completes, every time he forgives a sin, every single moment that he invites an outcast into relationship.

21:53.170 --> 22:02.680
Every single action he makes on earth is to set into motion his dream and his plan for Shalom, for humanity.

22:03.561 --> 22:04.562
He demonstrates

22:04.770 --> 22:11.241
This example of abundant life, of abundant peace, and then he fulfills it himself.

22:12.222 --> 22:15.868
As the prophet Isaiah said, but he was pierced for our transgressions.

22:16.289 --> 22:18.112
He was crushed for our iniquities.

22:18.533 --> 22:21.718
And the punishment that brought us peace was on him.

22:22.659 --> 22:24.663
And by his wounds, we are healed.

22:25.604 --> 22:29.170
At the cross, Jesus took the weight of humanity's sin

22:29.570 --> 22:36.082
the weight of that dysfunctional cycle, paying the ultimate price for our reconciliation with God.

22:36.984 --> 22:45.820
He accomplishes true Shalom by addressing the very root of the problem, the separation between God and humankind through sin.

22:46.441 --> 22:48.424
Through his death, he bridges that gap.

22:48.785 --> 22:53.714
He creates the ability for Shalom to come back and exist in the world through his spirit.

22:54.722 --> 22:59.648
Through this gesture of love, Jesus offers us shalom in the here and the now.

22:59.988 --> 23:05.755
He offers us healing and he offers restoration for every broken heart and every soul that is weary.

23:05.815 --> 23:11.902
Even if chaos still exists in our world around us, we can be secure in his shalom.

23:12.523 --> 23:14.325
But he takes it one step further.

23:14.785 --> 23:18.169
He invites us into shalom for all of eternity.

23:18.890 --> 23:22.194
And all we have to do is say yes to following him.

23:24.322 --> 23:29.209
I think what's really beautiful about this story is what it reveals about the nature of God.

23:29.950 --> 23:37.782
As many of you know, I was the kid's pastor in Ajax for a few years, and I learned a lot about how we teach the Bible to young people.

23:37.842 --> 23:53.906
This is my nerdy little kid's pastor, pet peeve, about Sunday school, and I somehow try to bring it up in every conversation I have about the Bible, but it's this idea we're up against when we read scripture called moralistic therapeutic deism.

23:54.402 --> 24:02.637
And it's essentially just a fancy word for basically reading scripture and trying to come up with the moral of the story to manage our sin.

24:03.418 --> 24:08.006
It's distilling scripture down to, if I do good, I will feel good theology.

24:09.108 --> 24:19.186
Scripture becomes this divine behavior manual, and we look for moral examples in the stories to follow, which isn't actually the good news of Jesus.

24:19.682 --> 24:24.669
But we often get stuck when we explain the Bible to our kids because there's a lot of nuance and there's a lot going on.

24:24.790 --> 24:27.253
And so it's hard to distill it down.

24:28.134 --> 24:36.086
But the problem with that theology of do good so I can feel better is that it often turns out that we make the humans, the heroes of the story.

24:36.647 --> 24:42.215
We point to a story like this in Sunday school and we say, look, look how Gideon overcame his fear.

24:42.295 --> 24:43.417
He was so brave.

24:43.437 --> 24:44.519
He faced adversity.

24:44.559 --> 24:46.481
He'd be more like Gideon, be fearless.

24:46.522 --> 24:49.586
Like how many of us remember that in Sunday school?

24:50.210 --> 24:52.893
But this story is not about Gideon.

24:53.433 --> 24:54.594
It's about God.

24:55.115 --> 24:58.838
It's about Yahweh Shalom.

24:58.858 --> 25:01.661
It's about how God is not conflict avoidant.

25:02.522 --> 25:13.993
To be honest, when our summer series was just a concept and I had a few names of God that I got to choose from to preach on, I picked Yahweh Shalom because I found it easy to connect with personally.

25:14.033 --> 25:19.378
I think I actively feel like God is a force of peace in my life.

25:19.746 --> 25:26.876
And so to be able to share that with you felt like such a privilege, such an important part of God's character to share.

25:26.916 --> 25:28.378
And I was so excited.

25:29.239 --> 25:30.761
But then I got to the assigned text.

25:30.821 --> 25:31.943
I got into judges six.

25:32.363 --> 25:33.685
And I was like, is this the wrong one?

25:34.066 --> 25:36.489
This one sets up for like a whole story of war.

25:36.709 --> 25:38.251
And like the piece doesn't even last.

25:38.852 --> 25:46.883
And so as I was unpacking the story and judges, I realized that this book is the most bloody and violent book in the whole Bible.

25:46.903 --> 25:49.106
And I was like, super, can't wait to do that.

25:49.794 --> 26:07.238
But the more and more I sat with it, the more I read it over and studied and the more I let the Holy Spirit kind of influence me and guide me in what I wanted to say and how He wanted me to speak about it, I realized that I had a really cheap version of peace that I was thinking about.

26:07.999 --> 26:12.485
I had my own shallow idea of what I believe peace to be, to unpack.

26:13.886 --> 26:19.474
And I know there's a percentage of us out there who don't mind conflict, but guys, I hate it.

26:19.874 --> 26:27.705
I hate that feeling of knowing you have a difficult conversation or knowing you have something to iron out with someone.

26:28.066 --> 26:30.950
I am so conflict avoided if I can help it.

26:31.471 --> 26:36.638
I actively have to fight the feeling of not shoving things down and avoiding it at all costs.

26:37.379 --> 26:41.906
Arguments to me in relationships feel like they threaten relational intimacy.

26:42.274 --> 26:43.415
Do you ever feel like that?

26:43.515 --> 26:47.619
Like you're afraid to say how you truly feel because you just want to avoid having the fight.

26:48.000 --> 26:51.423
You don't bring up the argument because you don't want to risk the relational fallout.

26:51.783 --> 26:57.048
You let the hurt in your friendships just fester and a fight because a fight just feels too painful.

26:57.088 --> 27:01.233
And the loss of relationship is at the cost of it.

27:01.853 --> 27:03.375
So you just bury it, you shove it down.

27:03.495 --> 27:09.200
And the problem is is that if you don't deal with it in a healthy way, it will end up dealing with you.

27:09.240 --> 27:10.962
If you end up

27:11.042 --> 27:15.990
You'll end up losing that connection with that person or you'll let bitterness start to grow in your heart.

27:18.133 --> 27:22.299
Our shallow idea of peace is not smoothing things over.

27:22.520 --> 27:25.164
It's smoothing things over, but that's not what God's idea is.

27:25.604 --> 27:33.096
And so while it's uncomfy and while it might not feel good, it is a very good thing that God is not conflict of wouldn't.

27:33.737 --> 27:39.666
When we look at the nature of God, we see that he always has the big picture of Shalom in mind.

27:40.066 --> 27:41.788
He is not afraid to step in.

27:41.868 --> 27:44.953
He is not afraid to write something that is wrong.

27:45.033 --> 27:47.216
He fights for injustice.

27:47.676 --> 27:50.680
We do not see him avoid the uncomfortable thing.

27:50.741 --> 27:52.082
He is not like us.

27:52.423 --> 27:55.447
He has the greater goal of Shalom in mind.

27:55.807 --> 27:57.990
He is not afraid of the messes that we make.

27:58.391 --> 28:00.975
He serves justice where it is needed.

28:01.015 --> 28:09.426
There's actually no situation that is too broken or too messy or too far gone that he cannot redeem or sort out

28:09.538 --> 28:09.979
or mend.

28:11.001 --> 28:14.687
See the shalom God has designed is not shove it down shalom.

28:15.108 --> 28:19.635
It is not avoid the war, avoid the chaos, avoid the conversation shalom.

28:20.457 --> 28:24.684
It is bring it into the light, fight the fight, find the true resolutions shalom.

28:25.485 --> 28:30.815
It often seeks out that discomfort and conflict because God is not a peace keeper.

28:30.955 --> 28:32.818
He is a peace maker.

28:33.250 --> 28:35.672
He cares too much to be conflict avoided.

28:35.873 --> 28:42.939
He loves us too much to leave us in the wake of our own destruction, even if we were the ones to cause it in the first place.

28:42.959 --> 28:50.126
Where the world and the flesh and the enemy steal, kill, and destroy, God actively chooses to chase peace down.

28:51.588 --> 28:55.692
Through His Son, Jesus, and through the restoration of all things.

28:56.212 --> 29:01.938
Jesus is the Prince of Peace, and what we actually see is Jesus waging war

29:02.050 --> 29:04.995
on our sins for the effort of true Shalom.

29:05.656 --> 29:11.666
And in this story, we see God actively pursuing peace, even if there's a big conflict to establish it.

29:12.146 --> 29:18.737
He will stop at nothing to establish Shalom, even our uncomfortability with conflict.

29:20.079 --> 29:29.074
The second thing that I think we see over the nature of God in this story is how God is with Gideon in the absence of peace.

29:29.762 --> 29:42.583
I'm sure Gideon would have loved it if God just smoothed over all the situations that were causing him worry and fear and anxiety, like if the minionights just vanished into thin air and it just sorted out all their problems.

29:43.345 --> 29:53.842
But I think in this book, we see time and time again how God doesn't always change our circumstances, but he promises to go with us instead.

29:54.690 --> 30:01.357
I think it's so interesting to see how God shows up for Gideon as he wrestles with his own anxiety in this story.

30:02.038 --> 30:05.082
Because it's easy to say, oh, look how brave Gideon was.

30:05.182 --> 30:16.114
But I think if you turn it around, you get to see a great example of how God interacts with those of us who struggle with fear and anxiety and doubt.

30:17.135 --> 30:23.442
You can just see God's kindness, his patience, his graciousness as he deals with Gideon

30:23.522 --> 30:30.248
ever so gently, letting Gideon test him over and over again in the name of just reassurance.

30:30.909 --> 30:32.831
He indulges all his worries.

30:33.111 --> 30:34.613
He does not invalidate him.

30:34.653 --> 30:37.175
He doesn't say to Gideon, I already told you I'm with you.

30:37.195 --> 30:38.756
Would you just leave it alone?

30:38.817 --> 30:41.539
He makes the fleece dry.

30:41.559 --> 30:46.844
He makes it wet, all in the name of love and patience and kindness.

30:47.905 --> 30:49.467
And then he goes with him.

30:50.127 --> 30:53.010
The God of Shalom can rule in your heart.

30:53.218 --> 30:58.823
while you struggle and while you wrestle and while you work out fear and anxiety in your life.

30:59.985 --> 31:04.769
First Peter five verse seven says, cast all your anxieties on him because he cares for you.

31:05.230 --> 31:16.480
And that's like a really nice thought to think, but unless you take God at his word, you'll have the tendency to do the opposite, to gather your worries and anxieties and to bottle them up and to carry them around yourself.

31:17.281 --> 31:20.524
But what does God do when Gideon cast his anxiety on him?

31:20.905 --> 31:22.226
When he cast his cares,

31:22.466 --> 31:27.253
when he worries to God, God takes a step closer.

31:27.894 --> 31:29.437
God reveals himself as peace.

31:29.857 --> 31:32.061
He's like a gracious and gentle father.

31:32.502 --> 31:33.483
God speaks to him.

31:33.724 --> 31:34.825
He shows up for him.

31:35.126 --> 31:37.229
He answers his questions again.

31:37.269 --> 31:38.511
He reassures him.

31:38.571 --> 31:40.214
He meets his needs.

31:41.315 --> 31:50.770
If that's you this morning, if you are struggling with fear and anxiety on a regular basis, I want to remind you that Jesus goes with you.

31:51.042 --> 32:03.339
He promises you the ultimate advocate, the ultimate comforter, his spirit, his own spirit of Shalom, his peace, which is far better than any sort of illusion than we can come up with ourselves.

32:04.861 --> 32:15.316
In John 14, Jesus says, but the advocate, the Holy Spirit, whom the Father will send in my name, will teach you all things, and will remind you of everything I have said to you.

32:15.837 --> 32:17.279
Peace, I leave with you.

32:17.880 --> 32:19.602
My peace, I give to you.

32:19.874 --> 32:21.436
I do not give as the world gives.

32:21.936 --> 32:25.681
Do not let your hearts be troubled and do not be afraid.

32:26.522 --> 32:30.487
God gives you his peace even in the middle of chaos.

32:30.927 --> 32:32.489
He does not give as the world gives.

32:33.551 --> 32:34.612
He gives you true shalom.

32:35.953 --> 32:44.063
I think the third thing that we really get to know about God through this story is that he invites us into the process of restoring shalom.

32:44.824 --> 32:47.708
God could have dealt with the minion nights any way that he wanted to.

32:47.748 --> 32:49.650
He's God.

32:49.762 --> 33:01.693
chooses to invite Gideon, who I'd argue is just a very average dude, into the process of creating shalom on the earth through freeing the Israelites from their oppressor.

33:02.214 --> 33:10.942
God's heart is for the earth to look like heaven, and he chooses to include us in that restoration process, even though he doesn't have to.

33:11.002 --> 33:19.090
But because he loves us and because he wants relationship with us, he chooses to invite us into that process.

33:20.066 --> 33:24.233
As I said before, dance didn't really work out, but swimming good.

33:24.673 --> 33:28.039
And I fell in love with the feeling of being in water.

33:28.179 --> 33:45.586
I love the feeling of peace that I have when I go under the water, I can feel my ears filled with water, which I know freaks people out, but I love that muffled noise of just, you can't hear noise, you can't hear other things, you're forced into quiet, you're forced into peace.

33:46.690 --> 33:59.410
And as I read this book a few years ago that piqued my interests because it had a swimming analogy, it reminded me of this idea, this idea that God invites us into the process of Shalom.

34:00.732 --> 34:07.983
It's Aaron Neekwist's book and he has this opening paragraph in the eternal current that is so beautiful.

34:08.023 --> 34:09.005
I want to read it for you today.

34:10.347 --> 34:12.210
A great and mighty river

34:12.322 --> 34:16.688
flows through history towards the healing and the restoration of all things.

34:17.469 --> 34:19.612
If you've read the Bible, you know how the story ends.

34:20.173 --> 34:21.755
Love conquers death.

34:22.516 --> 34:29.646
A new heaven and a new earth are established, and the God of love and justice finally puts all things right.

34:30.387 --> 34:35.814
Our Creator is carrying every corner of creation into a beautiful future.

34:35.854 --> 34:41.522
He goes on to use this analogy of the kingdom of God being like a river.

34:41.890 --> 34:54.602
an eternal current, the current of Christ that is woven in and throughout all things, always renewing, always restoring, where the things God wants to happen, happen on earth as it is in heaven.

34:55.463 --> 34:59.486
And he explains that you and I have been invited into the river to swim.

35:00.147 --> 35:06.153
He says, Jesus didn't merely invite me to believe about the river, to believe that it exists.

35:06.173 --> 35:08.815
He didn't say, here is the truth, believe me.

35:09.416 --> 35:11.858
He said, I am the truth, follow me.

35:12.418 --> 35:15.063
The invitation is participation.

35:16.065 --> 35:31.154
We are invited into God's eternal current of Shalom in all things, to swim in the river, to be active in the process, to live in wholeness with Him and with others, to participate in restoring where wholeness is not present in the world.

35:31.682 --> 35:34.445
It's fighting injustice like racism and poverty.

35:34.505 --> 35:37.608
It's taking care of the earth that he has blessed us with and made.

35:38.048 --> 35:45.536
It is treating other people made in the image of God, like they are made in the image of God with value and with love.

35:46.197 --> 35:52.022
It's showing God's love for all people in every single relationship you have, even the hard ones.

35:53.704 --> 35:55.086
It's really beautiful.

35:55.466 --> 35:59.570
It's a beautiful analogy if you let it be, but it requires trust.

36:00.642 --> 36:05.670
It requires trust that the one who is the source of the current knows what he's doing.

36:06.531 --> 36:09.536
Because peacemaking is an active role that God gives us.

36:09.956 --> 36:19.011
Participating in Yahweh Shalom's Shalom might look like having a difficult conversation you've been putting off with a family member you haven't spoken to in years.

36:19.692 --> 36:25.821
The river might float you by a friend that you need to reconcile with and apologize to for the sake of Shalom.

36:26.362 --> 36:28.946
You might pass some rapids that feel really scary.

36:29.282 --> 36:42.905
Shalom is hard and holy work, but God invites us to participate, not because he has to, but because he desires relationship with us, harmony with us, wholeness with us.

36:44.007 --> 36:54.024
I'd like to end our time today together by inviting God, Yahweh Shalom, our God of peace to have reign and rule in our life.

36:54.885 --> 36:55.506
Would you join me?

36:58.242 --> 37:01.666
So God, we thank you that you do not avoid conflict.

37:02.247 --> 37:07.273
We thank you that you enter into it with intention of making peace in our lives.

37:08.154 --> 37:13.761
We thank you, God, that even when peace feels far away or absent, you are with us.

37:14.622 --> 37:19.568
I pray for those of us who struggle with fear and anxiety, would you remind us of our reassurance in Christ?

37:20.109 --> 37:23.833
And would you remind us that you are a God who wants to reassure us?

37:24.254 --> 37:27.698
You want to remind us of your love and your shalom.

37:28.514 --> 37:35.464
And God, would we take you up on your invitation to get into the river and swim?

37:35.985 --> 37:40.652
Will we accept your offer to get into that current of Shalom in all things?

37:42.094 --> 37:45.920
To participate in the restoration of Shalom in your world.

37:46.360 --> 37:50.026
The work of joining you as you make the earth look more like heaven.

37:50.527 --> 37:58.258
Would you lead us and would you guide us for what that looks like individually in our lives as we trust you and as we follow you, God.

37:58.498 --> 38:00.165
Would you lead us and would you guide us?

38:00.506 --> 38:02.213
We pray this in Jesus' name.

38:03.197 --> 38:03.438
Amen.

38:04.201 --> 38:05.667
It was great to be with you this morning.

38:05.888 --> 38:06.450
See you later.

